<DIV1 N="29" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>CHAP. XXIX.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">A Maternal Eye.</HEAD>
<P>THE vivacity with which Camilla quitted Cleves,
was &s;unk before &s;he reached Etherington. She had
quitted al&s;o Edgar, quitted him offended, and in
doubt if it might ever be right &s;he &s;hould vindicate
her&s;elf in his opinion. Yet all &s;eemed &s;trange and
unintelligible that regarded the a&s;&s;erted nuptials: his
indifference was palpable; &s;he believed him to have
been unaccountably drawn in, and her heart &s;oftly
whi&s;pered, it was her&s;elf he preferred.</P>
<P>From this &s;oothing but dangerous idea, &s;he
&s;truggled to turn her thoughts. She anticipated the
remor&s;e of holding the affections of the hu&s;band of
her cou&s;in, and determined to u&s;e every po&s;&s;ible me|thod
to forget him&mdash;unle&s;s, which &s;he &s;trove vainly
not to hope, the reported alliance &s;hould never take
place.</P>
<P>The&s;e reflections &s;o completely engro&s;&s;ed her the
whole way, that &s;he arrived at the Par&s;onage Hou&s;e,
without the &s;malle&s;t mental preparation how to ac|count
for her return, or how to plead for remaining
at Etherington. Fore&s;ight, the offspring of judg|ment,
or the di&s;ciple of Experience, made no part
of the character of Camilla, who&s;e impetuous di&s;|po&s;ition
was open to every danger of indi&s;cretion,
<PB N="258" REF="67">
though her genuine love of virtue glowed warm with
juvenile ardour.</P>
<P>She entered, therefore, the breakfa&s;t parlour in a
&s;tate of &s;udden perplexity what to &s;ay; Mr. Tyrold
was alone and writing. He looked &s;urprized, but
embraced her with his accu&s;tomed affection, and en|quired
to what he owed her pre&s;ent &s;ight.</P>
<P>She made no an&s;wer; but embraced him again,
and enquired after her mother.</P>
<P>&startq;She is well,&endq; he replied: &startq;but, tell me, is
your uncle impatient of my delay? It has been wholly
unavoidable. I have been deeply engaged; and
deeply chagrined. Your poor mother would be &s;till
more di&s;turbed, if the noblene&s;s of her mind did not
&s;upport her.&endq;</P>
<P>Camilla, extremely grieved, earne&s;tly enquired
what had happened.</P>
<P>He then informed her that Mrs. Tyrold, the very
next morning, mu&s;t abruptly quit them all and &s;et
out for Li&s;bon to her &s;ick brother, Mr. Relvil.</P>
<P>&startq;Is he &s;o much wor&s;e?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;No: I even hope he is better. An act of folly
has brought this to bear. Do not now de&s;ire par|ticulars.
I will fini&s;h my letter, and then return
with you for a few minutes to Cleves. The carriage
mu&s;t wait.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Suffer me fir&s;t to a&s;k, does Lavinia go with my
mother?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;No, &s;he can only take old Ambro&s;e. Lavinia
mu&s;t &s;upply her place at home.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Ah! my deare&s;t father, and may not I, too,
&s;tay with you and a&s;&s;i&s;t her?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;If my brother will &s;pare you, my dear child,
there is nothing can &s;o much contribute to wile away
to me your mother's ab&s;ence.&endq;</P>
<P>Enchanted thus, without an$ explanation, to have
gained her point, &s;he completely revived; though
when Mrs. Tyrold, whom &s;he almo&s;t wor&s;hipped, en|tered
the room, in all the hurry of preparing for her
long journey, &s;he &s;hed a torrent of tears in her arms.</P>
<P><PB N="259" REF="68">
&startq;This good girl,&endq; &s;aid Mr. Tyrold, &startq;is her&s;elf
de&s;irous to quit the pre&s;ent gaities of Cleves, to try
to enliven my &s;olitude till we all may meet again.&endq;</P>
<P>The con&s;cious and artle&s;s Camilla could not bear
this unde&s;erved prai&s;e. She quitted her mother, and
returning to Mr. Tyrold, &startq;O my father!&endq; &s;he
cried, &startq;if you will take me again under your beloved
roof, it is for my &s;ake&mdash;not your's&mdash;I beg to re|turn!&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;She is right,&endq; &s;aid Mrs. Tyrold; &startq;there is no
merit in having an heart; &s;he could have none, if to
be with you were not her fir&s;t gratification.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Yes, indeed, my dear mother, it would always
be &s;o, even if no other inducement&mdash;.&endq; She &s;topt
&s;hort, confu&s;ed.</P>
<P>Mr. Tyrold, who continued writing, did not heed
this little blunder; but his wife, who&s;e quickne&s;s of
apprehen&s;ion and depth of ob&s;ervation, were always
alive, even in the mid&s;t of bu&s;ine&s;s, cares, and other
attentions, turned ha&s;tily to her daughter, and a&s;ked
to what &startq;other inducement&endq; &s;he alluded.</P>
<P>Camilla, di&s;tre&s;&s;ed, hung her head, and would
have forborne making any an&s;wer.</P>
<P>Mrs. Tyrold, then, putting down various packet$
which &s;he was &s;orting and &s;electing, came &s;uddenly
up to her, and taking both her hands, looked ear|ne&s;tly
in her face, &s;aying: &startq;My Camilla! &s;omething
has di&s;quieted you?&mdash;your countenance is not it&s;elf.
Tell me, my dear girl, what brought you hither this
morning? and what is it you mean by &s;ome other
inducement?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Do not a&s;k me now, my deare&s;t mother,&endq; an|&s;wered
&s;he, in a faultering voice; &startq;when you come
back again, no doubt all will be over; and then&mdash;&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;And is that the time, Camilla, to &s;peak to your
be&s;t friends? would it not be more judicious to be
explicit with them, while what affects you is &s;till de|pending?&endq;</P>
<P>Camilla, hiding her face on her mother's bo&s;om,
bur&s;t afre&s;h into tears.</P>
<P><PB N="260" REF="69">
&startq;Alas!&endq; cried Mrs. Tyrold, &startq;what new evil is
hovering? If it mu&s;t invade me again through one
of my children, tell me, at lea&s;t, Camilla, it is not
wilfully that you, too, afflict me? and afflict the
be&s;t of fathers?&endq;</P>
<P>Mr. Tyrold, dropping his pen, looked at them
both with the mo&s;t apprehen&s;ive anxiety.</P>
<P>&startq;No, my deare&s;t mother,&endq; &s;aid Camilla, endea|vouring
to meet her eyes; &startq;not wilfully,&mdash;but &s;ome|thing
has happened&mdash;I can hardly my&s;elf tell how or
what&mdash;but indeed Cleves, now&mdash;&endq; &s;he he&s;itated.</P>
<P>&startq;How is my brother?&endq; demanded Mr. Tyrold.</P>
<P>&startq;O! all that is good and kind! and I grieve to
quit him&mdash;but, indeed, Cleves, now&mdash;&endq; Again &s;he
he&s;itated.</P>
<P>&startq;Ah, my dear child!&endq; &s;aid Mrs. Tyrold, &startq;I
always feared that re&s;idence!&mdash;you are too young,
too incon&s;iderate, too innocent, indeed, to be left &s;o
utterly to your&s;elf.&mdash;Forgive me, my dear Mr. Ty|rold;
I do not mean to reflect upon your brother,
but he is not <HI>you!</HI>&mdash;and with you alone, this dear
inexperienced girl can be &s;ecure from all harm. Tell
me, however, what it is&mdash;?&endq;</P>
<P>Camilla, in the extreme&s;t confu&s;ion changed co|lour,
but tried vainly to &s;peak. Mr. Tyrold, &s;u&s;|pended
from all employment, waited fearfully &s;ome
explanation.</P>
<P>&startq;We have no time,&endq; &s;aid Mrs. Tyrold, &startq;for de|lay;&mdash;
you know I am going abroad,&mdash;and cannot
a&s;certain my return; though all my heart left be|hind
me, with my children and their father, will urge
every acceleration in my power.&endq;</P>
<P>Camilla wept again, fondly folding her arms round
her mother; &startq;I had hoped,&endq; &s;he cried, &startq;that I
&s;hould have come home to peace, comfort, tran|quillity!
to both of you, my deare&s;t father and mo|ther,
and to all my unbroken happine&s;s under your
roof!&mdash;How little did I dream of &s;o cruel a &s;epara|tion!&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Con&s;ole your&s;elf, my Camilla, that you have
not been its cau&s;e; may Heaven ever &s;pare me evil
<PB N="261" REF="70">
in your &s;hape at lea&s;t!&mdash;you &s;ay it is nothing wilful?
I can bear every thing el&s;e.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;We will not,&endq; &s;aid Mr. Tyrold, &startq;pre&s;s her;
&s;he will tell us all in her own way, and at her own
time. Forced confidence is neither fair nor flatter|ing.
I will excu&s;e her return to my brother, and
&s;he will the &s;ooner be able to give her account for
finding her&s;elf not hurried.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Calm your&s;elf, then,&endq; &s;aid Mrs. Tyrold, &startq;as
your indulgent father permits, and I will proceed
with my preparations.&endq;</P>
<P>Camilla now, &s;omewhat recovering, declared &s;he
had almo&s;t nothing to &s;ay; but her mother conti|nued
packing up, and her father went on with his
letter.</P>
<P>She had now time to con&s;ider that her own fears
and emotion were involving her in unnece&s;&s;ary con|fe&s;&s;ions;
&s;he re&s;olved, therefore, to repre&s;s the ful|ne&s;s
of her heart, and to acknowledge only the ac|cu&s;ation
of Mi&s;s Margland. And in a few minutes,
without waiting for further enquiry, &s;he gathered
courage to open upon the &s;ubject; and with as much
ea&s;e and quietne&s;s as &s;he could command, related, in
general terms, the charge brought again&s;t her, and
her con&s;equent de&s;ire to quit Cleves, &startq;till,&mdash;till
&mdash;&endq; Here &s;he &s;topt for breath. Mr. Tyrold in|&s;tantly
fini&s;hed the &s;entence, &startq;till the marriage has
taken place?&endq;</P>
<P>She coloured, and faintly uttered, &startq;Yes.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;You are right, my child,&endq; &s;aid he, &startq;and you
have acted with a prudence which does you honour.
Neither the able&s;t rea&s;oning, nor the mo&s;t upright
conduct, can &s;o completely obliterate a &s;urmi&s;e of
this nature, from a &s;u&s;picious mind, as ab&s;ence.
You &s;hall remain, therefore, with me, till your
cou&s;in is &s;ettled in her new habitation. Do you
know if the day is fixed?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;No, Sir,&endq; &s;he an&s;wered, while the ro&s;es fled
her cheeks at a que&s;tion which implied &s;o firm a be|lief
of the union.</P>
<P><PB N="262" REF="71">
&startq;Do not &s;uffer this affair to occa&s;ion you any
further unea&s;ine&s;s,&endq; he continued; &startq;it is the in|herent
and unalienable compact of Innocence with
Truth, to hold them&s;elves immovably &s;uperior to the
calumny of fal&s;e imputations. But I will go my&s;elf
to Cleves, and &s;et this whole matter right.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;And will you, too, Sir, have the goodne&s;s&mdash;&endq;
She was going to &s;ay, <HI>to make my peace with Edgar;</HI>
but the fear of mi&s;interpretation checked her, and
&s;he turned away.</P>
<P>He gently enquired what &s;he meant; &s;he avoided
any explanation, and he re&s;umed his writing.</P>
<P>Ah me! thought &s;he, will the time ever come,
when with openne&s;s, with propriety, I may clear
my&s;elf of caprice to Edgar?</P>
<P>Le&s;s patient, becau&s;e more alarmed than her hu&s;|band,
Mrs. Tyrold followed her to the window.
She &s;aw a tear in her eye, and again &s;he took both
her hands: &startq;Have you, my Camilla,&endq; &s;he cried,
&startq;have you told us all? Can unju&s;t impertinence &s;o
greatly have di&s;turbed you? Is there no &s;ting be|longing
to this wound that you are covering from
our &s;ight, though it may preci&s;ely be the &s;pot that
calls mo&s;t for &s;ome healing balm?&endq;</P>
<P>Again the cheeks of Camilla received their fugi|tive
ro&s;es. &startq;My deare&s;t mother,&endq; &s;he cried, &startq;is
not this enough?&mdash;to be accu&s;ed&mdash;&s;u&s;pected&mdash;and to
fear&mdash;&endq;</P>
<P>She &s;tammered, and would have withdrawn her
hands; but Mrs. Tyrold, &s;till holding them, &s;aid,
&startq;To fear what? &s;peak out, my be&s;t child! open
to us your whole heart!&mdash;Where el&s;e will you find
repo&s;itories &s;o tender?&endq;</P>
<P>Tears again flowed down the burning cheeks of
Camilla, and dropping her eyes, &startq;Ah, my mo|ther!&endq;
&s;he cried, &startq;you will think me &s;o frivolous&mdash;
you will blu&s;h &s;o for your daughter&mdash;if I own&mdash;if I
dare confe&s;s&mdash;&endq;</P>
<P>Again &s;he &s;topped, terrified at the conjectures to
which this opening might give birth; but when fur|ther
and fondly pre&s;&s;ed by her mother, &s;he added,
<PB N="263" REF="72">
&startq;It is not alone the&s;e unju&s;t &s;urmi&s;es,&mdash;nor even
Indiana's unkind concurrence in them&mdash;but al&s;o&mdash;I
have been afraid&mdash;I mu&s;t have made a &s;trange&mdash;a
capricious&mdash;an ungrateful appearance in the eyes of
Edgar Mandlebert.&endq;</P>
<P>Here her voice dropt; but pre&s;ently recovering,
&s;he rapidly continued, &startq;I know it is very immate|rial&mdash;
and I am &s;en&s;ible how fooli&s;h it may &s;ound&mdash;
but I &s;hall al&s;o think of it no more now,&mdash;and
therefore, as I have told the whole&mdash;&endq;</P>
<P>She looked up, con&s;cience &s;truck at the&s;e la&s;t
words, to &s;ee if they proved &s;atisfactory: &s;he
caught, in the countenance of her mother, an ex|pre&s;&s;ion
of deep commi&s;eration, which was followed
by a thou&s;and maternal care&s;&s;es of unu&s;ual &s;oftne&s;s,
though unaccompanied by any words.</P>
<P>Penetrated, yet di&s;tre&s;&s;ed, &s;he gratefully received
them, but rejoiced when, at length, Mr. Tyrold,
ri&s;ing, &s;aid, &startq;Go, my love, up &s;tairs to your &s;i&s;ter;
your mother, el&s;e, will never proceed with her
bu&s;ine&s;s.&endq;</P>
<P>She gladly ran off, and &s;oon, by a conci&s;e narra|tion,
&s;atisfied Lavinia, and then calmed her own
troubled mind.</P>
<P>Mr. Tyrold now, though evidently much affected
him&s;elf, &s;trove to compo&s;e his wife. &startq;Alas!&endq; cried
&s;he, &startq;do you not &s;ee what thus has touched me?
Do you not perceive that our lovely girl, more ju&s;t
to his worth than its po&s;&s;e&s;&s;or, has given her whole
heart to Edgar Mandlebert?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;I perceived it through your emotion, but I had
not di&s;covered it my&s;elf. I grieve, now, that the
probability of &s;uch an event had not &s;truck me in
time to have kept them apart for its prevention.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;I grieve for nothing,&endq; cried &s;he, warmly,
&startq;but the infatuated blindne&s;s of that &s;elf-lo&s;t young
man. What a wife would Camilla have made him in
every &s;tage of their united career! And how unfor|tunately
has &s;he &s;ympathi&s;ed in my &s;entiments, that
he alone &s;eemed worthy to replace the fir&s;t and be&s;t
protector &s;he mu&s;t relinqui&s;h when &s;he quits this
<PB N="264" REF="73">
hou&s;e! What will he find in Indiana but a beautiful
doll, unintere&s;ted in his feelings, unmoved by his ex|cellencies,
and incapable of comprehending him if
he &s;peaks either of bu&s;ine&s;s or literature!&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Yet many wives of this de&s;cription,&endq; replied
Mr. Tyrold, &startq;are more plea&s;ing in the eyes of their
hu&s;bands than women who are either better informed
in intellect, or more alive in &s;en&s;ation; and it is not
an uncommon idea among&s;t men, that where, both
in temper and affairs, there is lea&s;t participation,
there is mo&s;t repo&s;e. But this is not the ca&s;e with
Edgar.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;No! he has a nobler re&s;emblance than this por|trait
would allow him; a re&s;emblance which made
me hope from him a far higher &s;tyle of choice. He
prepares him&s;elf, however, his own ample puni&s;h|ment;
for he has too much under&s;tanding not to
&s;icken of mere per&s;onal allurements, and too much
genero&s;ity to be flattered, or &s;atisfied, by mere pa&s;|&s;ive
intellectual inferiority. Neither a mi&s;tre&s;s nor a
&s;lave can make him happy; a companion is what he
requires; and for that, in a very few months, how
vainly his &s;ecret &s;oul may &s;igh, and <HI>think of our
Camilla!</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>They then &s;ettled, that it would be now e&s;&s;ential
to the peace of their child to keep her as much as
po&s;&s;ible from his &s;ight; and determined not to &s;end
her back to Cleves to apologize for the new plan,
but to take upon them&s;elves that whole charge.
&startq;Her nature,&endq; &s;aid Mrs. Tyrold, &startq;is &s;o gay, &s;o
prompt for happine&s;s, that I have little fear but in
ab&s;ence &s;he will &s;oon cea&s;e to dwell upon him. Fear,
indeed, I have, but it is of a deeper evil than this
early impre&s;&s;ion; I fear for her future lot! With
whom can we tru&s;t her?&mdash;She will not endure negli|gence;
and tho&s;e &s;he cannot re&s;pect &s;he will &s;oon
de&s;pi&s;e. What a pro$pect for her, then, with our
pre&s;ent race of young men! their frivolous ficklene&s;s
nau&s;eates whatever they can reach; they have a weak
&s;hame of a&s;&s;erting, or even li&s;tening to what is right,
and a &s;hallow pride in profe&s;&s;ing and performing
<PB N="265" REF="74">
what is wrong. How mu&s;t this ingenuous girl for|get
all &s;he has yet &s;een, heard, or felt, ere &s;he can
encounter wickedne&s;s, or even weakne&s;s, and di&s;|gui&s;e
her abhorrence or contempt?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;My dear Georgiana, let us never look forward
to evil.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Will it not be doubly hard to bear, if it come
upon us without preparation?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;I think not. Terror &s;hakes, and apprehen&s;ion
depre&s;&s;es: hope nerves as well as gladdens us. Re|member
always, I do not by hope mean pre&s;ump|tion;
I mean &s;imply a chearful tru&s;t in heaven.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;I mu&s;t always yield,&endq; cried Mrs. Tyrold, &startq;to
your &s;uperior wi&s;dom, and reflecting piety; and if I
cannot conquer my fears, at lea&s;t I will neither
court nor indulge them.&endq;</P>
<P>The thanks of a grateful hu&s;band repaid this
compliance. They &s;ent for Camilla, to acquaint her
they would make her excu&s;es at Cleves: &s;he gave a
ready though melancholy con&s;ent, and the virtue of
her motives drew tears from her idolizing mother, as
&s;he cla&s;ped her to her heart.</P>
<P>They then &s;et out together, that Mr. Tyrold
might arrange this bu&s;ine&s;s with Sir Hugh, of whom
and of Eugenia Mrs. Tyrold was to take leave.</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="30" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>CHAP. XXX.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Modern Ideas of Duty.</HEAD>
<P>CAMILLA now felt more permanently revived,
becau&s;e better &s;atisfied with the rectitude of her
conduct. She could no longer be accu&s;ed of inter|fering
between Edgar and Indiana; that affair
would take its natural cour&s;e, and, be it what it
might, while ab&s;ent from both parties, &s;he concluded
&s;he &s;hould at lea&s;t e&s;cape all cen&s;ure.</P>
<P>Peaceably, therefore, &s;he returned to take po&s;&s;e&s;|&s;ion
of her u&s;ual apartment, affectionately accom|panied
by her elde&s;t &s;i&s;ter.</P>
<P><PB N="266" REF="75">
The form and the mind of Lavinia were in the
mo&s;t perfect harmony. Her poli&s;hed complexion
was fair, clear, and tran&s;parent; her features were
of the extreme&s;t delicacy, her eyes of the &s;ofte&s;t
blue, and her &s;mile di&s;played internal &s;erenity. The
unru&s;&s;led &s;weetne&s;s of her di&s;po&s;ition bore the &s;ame
character of mode&s;t excellence. Joy, hope, and
pro&s;perity, &s;ickne&s;s, &s;orrow, and di&s;appointment,
a&s;&s;ailed alike in vain the uniform gentlene&s;s of her
temper: yet though thus exempt from all natural
turbulence, either of plea&s;ure or of pain, the meek|ne&s;s
of her compo&s;ition degenerated not into in&s;en|&s;ibility;
it was open to all the feminine feelings of
pity, of &s;ympathy, and of tenderne&s;s.</P>
<P>Thus copiou&s;ly gifted with &startq;all her &s;ex's &s;oft|ne&s;s,&endq;
her &s;ociety would have contributed to re&s;tore
Camilla to repo&s;e, had they continued together
without interruption; but, in a few minutes, the
room door was opened, and Lionel, ru&s;hing into the
apartment, called out, &startq;How do, do, my girls?
how do, do?&endq; and &s;hook them each by the hand,
with a &s;wing that nearly brought them to the
ground.</P>
<P>Camilla always rejoiced at his &s;ight; but La|vinia
gravely &s;aid, &startq;I thought, brother, you had
been at Dr. Marchmont's?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;All in good time, my dear! I &s;hall certainly
vi&s;it the old gentleman before long.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Did you not &s;leep there, then, la&s;t night?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;No, child.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Good God, Lionel!&mdash;if my mother&mdash;&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;My dear little Lavinia,&endq; cried he, chucking
her under the chin, &startq;I have a va&s;t notion of making
vi&s;its at my own time, in&s;tead of my mamma's.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;O Lionel! and can you, ju&s;t now&mdash;&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Come, come,&endq; interrupted he, &startq;don't let us
wa&s;te our precious minutes in old moralizing. If I
had not luckily been hard by, I &s;hould not have
known the coa&s;t was clear. Pray where are they
gone, tantivying?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;To Cleves.&endq;</P>
<P><PB N="267" REF="76">
&startq;To Cleves! what a happy e&s;cape! I was upon
the point of going thither my&s;elf. Camilla, what
is the matter with thee?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Nothing&mdash;I am only thinking&mdash;pray when do
you go to Oxford?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Pho, pho,&mdash;what do you talk of Oxford for?
you are grown quite &s;tupid, girl. I believe you
have lived too long with Mi&s;s Margland. Pray how
does that dear creature do? I am afraid &s;he will
grow melancholy from not &s;eeing me &s;o long. Is
&s;he as pretty as &s;he u&s;ed to be? I have &s;ome notion
of &s;ending her a &s;uitor.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;O brother,&endq; &s;aid Lavinia, &startq;is it po&s;&s;ible you
can have &s;uch &s;pirits?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;O hang it, if one is not merry when one can,
what is the world good for? be&s;ides, I do a&s;&s;ure
you, I fretted &s;o con&s;umed hard at fir&s;t, that for the
life of me I can fret no longer.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;But why are you not at Dr. Marchmont's?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Becau&s;e, my dear, you have no conception the
plea&s;ure tho&s;e old doctors take in lecturing a young|&s;ter
who is in any di&s;grace.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Di&s;grace!&endq; repeated Camilla.</P>
<P>&startq;At all events,&endq; &s;aid Lavinia, &startq;I be&s;eech you
to be a little careful; I would not have my poor mo|ther
find you here for the world.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;O, as to that, I defy her to de&s;ire the meeting
le&s;s than I do. But come, let's talk of &s;omething
el&s;e. How go on the cla&s;&s;ics? Is my old friend, Dr.
Orkborne, as chatty and amu&s;ing as ever?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;My dear Lionel,&endq; &s;aid Camilla. &startq;I am filled
with apprehen&s;ion and perplexity. Why &s;hould my
mother wi&s;h not to &s;ee you? And why&mdash;and how is
it po&s;&s;ible you can wi&s;h not to &s;ee her?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;What, don't you know it all?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;I know only that &s;omething mu&s;t be wrong;
but how, what, or which way, I have not heard.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Has not Lavinia told you, then?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;No,&endq; an&s;wered Lavinia; &startq;I could be in no
ha&s;te to give her pain.&endq;</P>
<P><PB N="268" REF="77">
&startq;You are a good girl enough. But how came
you hither, Camilla? and what is the rea&s;on you
have not &s;een my mother your&s;elf?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Not &s;een her! I have been with her this half
hour.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;What! and in all that time did not &s;he tell
you?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;She did not name you.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Is it po&s;&s;ible!&mdash;Well, &s;he's a noble creature!
I wonder how &s;he could ever have &s;uch a &s;on as me.
And I am &s;till le&s;s like my father than her. I &s;up|po&s;e
I was changed in the cradle. Will you coun|tenance
me, young ladies, if &s;ome villainous attor|ney
or exci&s;eman &s;hould by and by come to own me?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Dear Lionel,&endq; cried Camilla, &startq;do explain to
me what has happened. You make me think it im|portant
and trifling twenty times in a minute.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;O, a horrid bu&s;ine&s;s!&mdash;Lavinia mu&s;t tell it
you. I'll go away till &s;he has done. Don't de&s;pi&s;e
me, Camilla; I am confounded &s;orry, I promi&s;e
you.&endq;</P>
<P>He then hurried out of the room, evidently feel|ing
more emotion than he cared to di&s;play.</P>
<P>Yet Lavinia had but ju&s;t begun her relation, when
he abruptly returned. &startq;Come, I had better tell it
you my&s;elf,&endq; cried he, &startq;for &s;he'll make &s;uch a di&s;|mal
ditty of it, that it won't be over this half year;
the &s;ooner we have done with it the better; it will
only put you out of &s;pirits.&endq;</P>
<P>Then, &s;itting down, and taking her hand, he
began, &startq;You mu&s;t know I was in rather a bad &s;crape
at Oxford la&s;t year&mdash;&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;La&s;t year! and you never told us of it before!&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;O, 'twas about &s;omething you would not un|der&s;tand,
&s;o I &s;hall not mention particulars now. It
is enough for you to know that two or three of us
wanted a little ca&s;h!&mdash;well, &s;o&mdash;in &s;hort, I &s;ent a
letter&mdash;&s;omewhat of a threatening &s;ort&mdash;to poor old
uncle Relvil!&endq;&mdash;</P>
<P>&startq;O Lionel!&endq;</P>
<P><PB N="269" REF="78">
&startq;O, I did not &s;ign it,&mdash;it was only begging a
little money, which he can afford to &s;pare very well;
and ju&s;t telling him, if he did not come to a place I
mentioned, he would have his brains blown out.&endq;&mdash;</P>
<P>&startq;How horrible!&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Pho, pho,&mdash;he had only to &s;end the money,
you know, and then his brains might keep their
place; be&s;ides, you can't &s;uppo&s;e there was gun|powder
in the words. So I got this copied, and
took the proper mea&s;ures for concealment, and,&mdash;
would you believe it! the poor old gull was fool
enough actually to &s;end the money where he was
bid?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Fie, Lionel!&endq; cried Lavinia; &startq;do you call
him a fool becau&s;e you terrified him?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Yes, to be &s;ure, my dear; and you both think
him &s;o too, only you don't hold it pretty to &s;ay &s;o.
Do you &s;uppo&s;e, if he had had half the wit of his
&s;i&s;ter, he would have done it? I believe, in my con|&s;cience,
there was &s;ome odd mi&s;take in their births,
and that my mother took away the brains of the
man, and left the woman's for the noddle of my
poor uncle.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Fie, fie, brother!&endq; &s;aid Lavinia again; &startq;you
know how &s;ickly he has always been from his birth,
and how &s;oon therefore he might be alarmed.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Why, yes, Lavinia&mdash;I believe it was a very
bad thing&mdash;and I would give half my little &s;inger I
had not done it. But it's over, you know; &s;o what
&s;ignifies making the wor&s;t of it?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;And did he not di&s;cover you?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;No; I gave him particular orders, in my letter,
not to attempt any thing of that &s;ort, a&s;&s;uring him
there were &s;pies about him to watch his proceed|ings.
The good old a&s;s took it all for go&s;pel. So
there the matter dropt. However, as ill luck would
have it, about three months ago we wanted another
&s;um&mdash;&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;And could you again&mdash;&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Why, my dear, it was only taking a little of
my own fortune before-hand, for I am his heir; &s;o
<PB N="270" REF="79">
we all agreed it was merely robbing my&s;elf; for we
had &s;everal con&s;ultations about it, and one of us is
to be a lawyer.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;But you give me &s;ome plea&s;ure here,&endq; &s;aid Ca|milla;
&startq;for I had never heard that my uncle had
made you his heir.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;No more have I neither, my dear; but I take
it for granted. Be&s;ides, our little lawyer put it into
my head. Well, we wrote again, and told the poor
old gentleman&mdash;for which I a&s;&s;ure you I am heartily
repentant&mdash;that if he did not &s;end me double the
&s;um, in the &s;ame manner, without delay, his hou&s;e
was to be burnt to the ground the fir&s;t night that he
and all his family were a&s;leep in bed.&mdash;Now don't
make faces and &s;hruggings, for, I promi&s;e you, I
think already I de&s;erve to be hanged for giving him
the fright; though I would not really have hurt
him, all the time, for half his fortune. And who
could have gue&s;&s;ed he would have bit &s;o ea&s;ily? The
money, however, came, and we thought it all &s;e|cure,
and agreed to get the &s;ame &s;um annually.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Annually!&endq; repeated Camilla, with uplifted
hands.</P>
<P>&startq;Yes, my dear. You have no conception how
convenient it would have been for our extra ex|pences.
But, unluckily, uncle grew wor&s;e, and
went abroad, and then con&s;ulted with &s;ome crab of
a friend, and that friend with &s;ome demagogue of a
magi&s;trate, and &s;o all is blown!&mdash;However, we had
managed it &s;o cleverly, it co&s;t them near three
months to find it out, owing, I mu&s;t confe&s;s, to
poor uncle's cowardice in not making his enquiries
before the money was carried off, and he him&s;elf
over the &s;eas and far away. The other particulars
Lavinia mu&s;t give you; for I have talked of it now
till I have made my&s;elf quite fick. Do tell me
&s;omething diverting to drive it a little out of my
head. Have you &s;een any thing of my enchanting
widow lately?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;No, &s;he does not de&s;ire to be &s;een by me. She
would not admit me.&endq;</P>
<P><PB N="271" REF="80">
&startq;She is frankne&s;s it&s;elf, and does not pretend to
care a fig for any of her own &s;ex.&mdash;O, but, Camilla,
I have wanted to a&s;k you this great while, if you
think there is any truth in this rumour, that Mandle|bert
intends to propo&s;e to Indiana?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;To propo&s;e! I thought it had all long &s;ince
been &s;ettled.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Ay, &s;o the world &s;ays; but I don't believe a
word of it. Do you think, if that were the ca&s;e,
he would not have owned it to me? There's nothing
fixed yet, depend upon it.&endq;</P>
<P>Camilla, &s;truck, amazed, and delighted, invo|luntarily
embraced her brother; though, recollect|ing
her&s;elf almo&s;t at the &s;ame moment, &s;he endea|voured
to turn off the re&s;i&s;tle&s;s impul&s;e into taking
leave, and hurrying him away.</P>
<P>Lionel, who to want of &s;olidity and penetration
principally owed the errors of his conduct, was ea&s;ily
put upon a wrong &s;eent, and a&s;&s;ured her he would
take care to be off in time. &startq;But what,&endq; cried he,
&startq;has carried them to Cleves? Are they gone to tell
tales? Becau&s;e I have lo&s;t one uncle by my own
fault, mu&s;t I lo&s;e another by their's?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;No,&endq; an&s;wered Lavinia, &startq;they have deter|mined
not to name you. They have &s;ettled that my
uncle Hugh &s;hall never be told of the affair, nor any
body el&s;e, if they can help it, except your &s;i&s;ters,
and Dr. Marchmont.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Well, they are good &s;ouls,&endq; cried he, at|tempting
to laugh, though his eyes were gli&s;tening;
&startq;I wi&s;h I de&s;erved them better; I wi&s;h, too, it
was not &s;o dull to be good. I can be merry and
harmle&s;s here at the &s;ame time,&mdash;and &s;o I can at
Cleves;&mdash;but at Oxford&mdash;or in London,&mdash;your
merry blades there&mdash;I can't deny it, my dear &s;i&s;ters
&mdash;your merry blades there are but &s;ad fellows. Yet
there is &s;uch fun, &s;uch &s;pirit, &s;uch &s;port among&s;t
them, I cannot for my life keep out of their way.
Be&s;ides, you have no conception, young ladies, what
a bye-word you become among them if they catch
you flinching.&endq;</P>
<P><PB N="272" REF="81">
&startq;I would not for the world &s;ay any thing to pain
you, my dear brother,&endq; cried Lavinia; &startq;but yet I
mu&s;t hope that, in future, your fir&s;t &s;tudy will be to
re&s;i&s;t &s;uch dangerous examples, and to drop &s;uch un|worthy
friends?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;If it is not to tell tales, then, for what el&s;e are
they gone to Cleves, ju&s;t at this time?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;For my mother to take leave of Eugenia and
my uncle before her journey.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Journey! Why, whither i$ &s;he going!&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Abroad.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;The deuce &s;he is!&mdash;And what for?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;To try to make your peace with her brother;
or at lea&s;t to nur&s;e him her&s;elf till he is tolerably re|covered.&endq;</P>
<P>Lionel flapped his hat over his eyes, and &s;aying,
&startq;This is too much!&mdash;if I were a man I &s;hould &s;hoot
my&s;elf!&endq;&mdash;ru&s;hed out of the room.</P>
<P>The two &s;i&s;ters rapidly followed him, and caught
his arm before he could quit the hou&s;e. They ear|ne&s;tly
be&s;ought him to return, to compo&s;e him&s;elf,
and to promi&s;e he would commit no ra&s;h action.</P>
<P>&startq;My dear &s;i&s;ters,&endq; cried he, &startq;I am worked ju&s;t
now only as I ought to be; but I will give you any
promi&s;e you plea&s;e. However, though I have never
li&s;tened to my father as I ought to have li&s;tened, he
has implanted in my mind a horror of &s;uicide, that
will make me live my natural life, be it as good for
nothing as it may.&endq;</P>
<P>He then &s;uffered his &s;i&s;ters to lead him back to
their room, where he ca&s;t him&s;elf upon a chair, in
painful rumination upon his own unworthine&s;s, and
his parents excellence; but the tender &s;oothings of
Lavinia and Camilla, who trembled le&s;t his remor&s;e
&s;hould urge him to &s;ome act of violence, &s;oon drew
him from reflections of which he hated the intru&s;ion:
and he attended, with complacency, to their youth|ful
&s;ecurity of perfect reconciliations, and re-e&s;ta|bli&s;hed
happine&s;s.</P>
<P>With reciprocal exultation, the eyes of the &s;i&s;ters
congratulated each other on having &s;aved him from
<PB N="273" REF="82">
de&s;pair: and &s;eeing him now calm, and, they hoped,
&s;afe, they mutually, though tacitly, agreed to ob|trude
no further upon meditations that might be u&s;e|ful
to him, and remained &s;ilently by his &s;ide.</P>
<P>For &s;ome minutes all were profoundly &s;till; Lionel
then &s;uddenly &s;tarted up; the &s;i&s;ters, affrighted, ha&s;|tily
aro&s;e at the &s;ame in&s;tant; when &s;tretching him|&s;elf
and yawning, he called out, &startq;Pr'ythee, Ca|milla,
what is become of that &s;mug Mr. Dub&s;ter?&endq;</P>
<P>Speechle&s;s with amazement, they looked earne&s;tly
in his face, and feared he was raving.</P>
<P>They were &s;oon, however undeceived; the tide
of penitence and &s;orrow was turned in his buoyant
&s;pirits, and he was only re&s;tored to his natural vo|latile
&s;elf.</P>
<P>&startq;You u&s;ed him mo&s;t &s;habbily,&endq; he continued,
&startq;and he was a very pretty fellow. The next time
I have nothing better to do, I'll &s;end him to you,
that you may make it up.&endq;</P>
<P>This quick return of gaiety cau&s;ed a &s;igh to La|vinia,
and much &s;urpri&s;e to Camilla; but neither of
them could prevail with him to depart, till Mr. and
Mrs. Tyrold were every moment expected; they then,
though with infinite difficulty, procured his promi&s;e
that he would go &s;traight to Dr. Marchmont, ac|cording
to an arrangement made for that purpo&s;e by
Mrs. Tyrold her&s;elf.</P>
<P>Lavinia, when he was gone, related &s;ome circum|&s;tances
of this affair which he had omitted. Mr.
Relvil, the elder brother of Mrs. Tyrold, was a
country gentleman of &s;ome fortune, but of weak
parts, and an invalid from his infancy. He had &s;uf|fered
the&s;e incendiary letters to prey upon his repo&s;e,
without venturing to produce them to any one, from
a terror of the menaces hurled again&s;t him by the
writer, till at length he became &s;o completely hypo|chondriac,
that his re&s;t was utterly broken, and, to
pre&s;erve his very exi&s;tence, he re&s;olved upon vi&s;iting
another climate.</P>
<P>The day that he &s;et out for Li&s;bon, his de&s;tined
harbour, he delivered his anonymous letters to a
<PB N="274" REF="83">
friend, to whom he left in charge to di&s;cover, if
po&s;&s;ible, their author.</P>
<P>This di&s;covery, by the u&s;ual means of enquiries
and rewards, was &s;oon made; but the moment Mr.
Relvil learnt that the culprit was his nephew, he
wrote over to Mrs. Tyrold a &s;tatement of the tran&s;|action,
declaring he &s;hould di&s;inherit Lionel from
every &s;hilling of his e&s;tate. His health was &s;o much
impaired, he &s;aid, by the di&s;turbance this had given
to his mind, that he &s;hould be obliged to &s;pend the
en&s;uing year in Portugal; and he even felt uncertain
if he might ever return to his own country.</P>
<P>Mrs. Tyrold, a&s;toni&s;hed and indignant, &s;everely
que&s;tioned her &s;on, who, covered with &s;hame, &s;ur|pri&s;e,
and repentance, confe&s;&s;ed his guilt. Shocked
and grieved in the extreme, &s;he ordered him from her
&s;ight, and wrote to Dr. Marchmont to receive him.
She then &s;ettled with Mr. Tyrold the plan of her
journey and voyage, hoping by &s;o immediately fol|lowing,
and her&s;elf nur&s;ing her incen&s;ed brother,
to &s;often his wrath, and avert its final ill con&s;e|quences.</P>
